In Fig. 7.3(b), a PMOS current mirror $Q_{3 / 4}$ is introduced to generate an intermediate current $I_{d}$ that is transmitted across the chip. Unlike Fig. 7.3(a), here the long wire carries a non-zero current, making this a "current-mode" approach to bias distribution. It is preferred because both pairs of current mirror devices are co-located, ensuring their currents are well-matched. While the simple current mirrors in Fig. 7.3 can be replaced by high output impedance variants for better accuracy, the fundamental advantage of current-mode bias distribution remains. Current-mode distribution may consume more power and area due to additional devices and bias current required. However, these drawbacks are mitigated by the fact that $Q_{1}$ and $Q_{3}$ in Fig. 7.3(b) can be made small, and the current $I_{d}$ reduced, minimizing the added power and area. ${ }^{1}$

