The foundation for numerous bipolar bandgap references was laid by the design proposed in Brokaw's 1974 work. The core circuit, a simplified version of which is depicted in Fig. 7.10, hinges on an amplifier that equalizes the collector voltages of transistors $Q_{1}$ and $Q_{2}$. Given that $R_{3}=R_{4}$, it's ensured that both transistors experience identical collector currents and collector-emitter voltages. Additionally, the emitter area of $Q_{1}$ is eightfold compared to that of $Q_{2}$, leading to a current density in $Q_{2}$ that is eight times that of $Q_{1}$, expressed as:

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{J_{2}}{J_{1}}=8 \tag{7.30}
\end{equation*}
$$

For this circuit, the reference voltage is given by:

$$
\begin{equation*}
V_{\text {ref }}=V_{B E 2}+V_{R 1} \tag{7.31}
\end{equation*}
$$

And we also have:

$$
\begin{align*}
V_{\mathrm{R} 1} & =\mathrm{I}_{\mathrm{R} 1} \mathrm{R}_{1} \\
& =2 \mathrm{I}_{\mathrm{R}_{2}} \mathrm{R}_{1} \tag{7.32}
\end{align*}
$$

[Textual description of Fig. 7.10 is provided.]

Moreover,

$$
\begin{equation*}
\mathrm{I}_{\mathrm{R} 2}=\frac{\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{R} 2}}{\mathrm{R}_{2}}=\frac{\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{BE} 2}-\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{BE} 1}}{\mathrm{R}_{2}}=\frac{\Delta \mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{BE}}}{\mathrm{R}_{2}} \tag{7.33}
\end{equation*}
$$

Inserting (7.32) and (7.33) into (7.31) results in:

$$
\begin{equation*}
\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{ref}}=\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{BE} 2}+\frac{2 \mathrm{R}_{1}}{\mathrm{R}_{2}} \Delta \mathrm{~V}_{\mathrm{BE}} \tag{7.34}
\end{equation*}
$$

This is the desired form for a bandgap reference. It's clear that:

$$
\begin{equation*}
\mathrm{K}=\frac{2 \mathrm{R}_{1}}{\mathrm{R}_{2}} \tag{7.35}
\end{equation*}
$$

